<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-181-184 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 580 192</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 9 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Comtex exhibition opens in Moscow.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tchashchin, Kirill.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Comtex Expositions (Conferences and meetings).andO;Topic:     Trade showsComtex (Trade show).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>COMTEX EXHIBITION OPENS IN MOSCOW 04/09/91 MOSCOW, U.S.S.R., 1991 APR 9 (NB)-- The sounds of a massive orchestra striking up a tune marked the openingceremony for the second annual Comtex exhibition in Moscow this week.andP;  Theorganizers said that they expect attendance at the show to be double that oflast year.andM;The week-long exhibition is organized by Comtex Expositions of Wilton,Connecticut, U.S.A.andP;  and co-sponsored by Business Week/U.S.S.R.,  theMoscow-based Joint-venture Crocus International, Computerland, and PCMagazine.andM;Among the more than 150 companies from the U.S.andP;  announcing new products atthe show was Digital Equipment, which took the largest stand at Comtex.andM;While there are clearly many different problems for Western companies intenton marketing their products in the U.S.S.R., the major one, even for thesuccessful companies, is how to convert the roubles into dollars or otherWestern currencies.andM;Several seminars and workshops are scheduled to take place this week toaddress the problem, and the myriad of other difficulties that face Westerncompanies in the increasingly liberalized Russian technology marketplace.andO;Speakers from several leading U.S.andP;  technology companies have been lined up,including 3M, Nuntucket, Unix International, Sun Microsystems, Ziff-Davis,Lotus Development, Symantec, Borland and Autodesk.andM;(Kirill Tchashchin/19910409)</TEXT></DOC>